    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36a.16"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        400 North Garth, Apt. 612
                        Columbia, Missouri
                        June 17, 1972
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>You probably do not remember me, but a number of years ago when I taught at the then Christian College you were kind enough to speak to my literature students and read them some of your poetry. I am now retired, but I remember the occasion, and you with admiration.</p>
                
                <p>A few nights ago when I listened to you on the Dick Cavett show I was moved and feel I would like you to know how much I appreciate the things you said. You presente<unclear reason="missing">d</unclear> the poet's vision &#8212; little heard o<unclear reason="missing">n</unclear> television &#8212; and a realistic understanding of the American Indian which white citizens need to hear.</p> 
                
                <p>Please accept my sincere admiration and respect, and my thanks for the inspiration you have given me.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Cynthia McHarg
                    (Mrs. W. I. McHarg)</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">16</fw>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
